messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Here is the analysis based on the provided files.

What is the full path prefix for the book endpoints?
- The v1 API is mounted at /v1 (via app/__init__.py).
- The book endpoints are mounted at /book inside the v1 blueprint.
- Therefore, all book endpoints live under the prefix /v1/book.
- Path parameters in OpenAPI style should use curly braces.

Endpoints and their accepted HTTP methods (as defined by the code)
- GET /v1/book/{id}
  - Handler: get_book(id)
  - Acceptable methods: GET
  - Note: HEAD is automatically handled by Flask for GET routes; OPTIONS is also automatically provided.

- GET /v1/book
  - Handler: get_books()
  - Acceptable methods: GET

- GET /v1/book/search
  - Handler: search(query)
  - Acceptable methods: GET

- POST /v1/book
  - Handler: create_book(json)
  - Acceptable methods: POST

- PUT /v1/book/{id}
  - Handler: update_book(id, json)
  - Acceptable methods: PUT

- DELETE /v1/book/{id}
  - Handler: delete_book(id)
  - Acceptable methods: DELETE

Which HTTP methods are accepted overall (and overrides)
- All methods are not universally accepted. The code only defines explicit routes with GET, POST, PUT, and DELETE for the above endpoints.
- HEAD and OPTIONS are not explicitly defined, but Flask/Werkzeug provide sensible behavior:
  - HEAD is effectively allowed when a GET route exists (as in the GET routes above).
  - OPTIONS is automatically handled for endpoints that exist (Flask provides an automatic options response unless disabled).
- PATCH is not defined for any route in the provided code, so PATCH is not acceptable.
- TRACE is not defined or handled by the code, so TRACE is not acceptable.

Summary of acceptability per method (based on code)
- All HTTP methods: No (not all methods are defined; only GET, POST, PUT, DELETE are explicitly implemented).
- HEAD: Yes (implicit support via Flask for GET routes).
- POST: Yes (via /v1/book, POST).
- OPTIONS: Yes (implicit support via Flask for existing routes).
- TRACE: No (not implemented in code).
- GET: Yes (via /v1/book and /v1/book/{id} and /v1/book/search).
- PUT: Yes (via /v1/book/{id}).
- DELETE: Yes (via /v1/book/{id}).
- PATCH: No (not implemented in code).

Explanation
- The full path prefix is /v1 (from app/__init__.py) plus /book (from app/api/v1/__init__.py), giving /v1/book as the base for all book endpoints.
- Each endpointâ€™s path is derived from the route decorators:
  - "" under the book blueprint becomes /v1/book
  - "/<int:id>" becomes /v1/book/{id}
  - "/search" becomes /v1/book/search
- HTTP method support is determined by the methods parameter in the route decorator. If absent, Flask defaults to GET, and HEAD/OPTIONS are handled automatically for GET routes. No route defines PATCH or TRACE, so those methods are not supported by the code.
